entry.summary:

Portneuf River at Pocatello affecting Bannock County.
* WHAT...Moderate flooding is forecast.

* WHEN...Until further notice.
* IMPACTS...At 8.5 feet, Sections of Sacajawea Park will be under water and the trail is usually closed at this level. Marsh Creek near Inkom may also be over its banks. Lowland flooding is likely along sections of the river between Portneuf Gap and the Cheyenne Avenue Bridge in Pocatello. At 9.4 feet, Water will encroach around sitting benches near the river at the Pacific Recycling Trailhead. At 10.0 feet, Significant flooding of agricultural land will occur from the Inkom and Blackrock area. Lowland flooding will occur along sections of the river in Pocatello from Portneuf Gap to the Cheyenne Avenue Bridge and downstream of the concrete channel beginning at Sacajawea Park.

entry.title: Hydrologic Outlook issued April 9 at 3:28PM CDT by NWS Chicago IL
entry.summary:
ESFLOT
Flooding of rivers, creeks, ditches, and poor drainage areas possible across northeastern Illinois and northwestern Indiana later this week. Significant river rises and renewed flooding possible along the Iroquois, Kankakee, Des Plaines, Fox, and Illinois rivers.
Rainfall is expected to develop and move into the Midwest during the day on Wednesday and continue through Thursday night. Widespread rainfall of at least half an inch is likely, with localized totals near 2 to 3 inches possible. Runoff from this rainfall will be increased due to high soil moisture values across the region due to recent wet weather. Significant rises are possible on area streams and rivers, including the possibility of renewed flooding on the Iroquois, Kankakee, Des Plaines, Fox, and Illinois rivers and their tributaries. In addition to flooding of larger rivers, flooding of fields, ditches, and poor drainage areas may also occur. Confidence in the exact placement of rainfall and the exact rainfall totals remains low at this time, which prevents more specific forecasts.
This outlook means that elevated water levels and potential impacts are possible, but not yet certain. Persons with interests along area rivers should closely monitor the latest forecasts including the possibility of flood watches, warnings, and advisories.
This product may be updated tomorrow if the possibility of heavy rainfall and flooding continues.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued April 9 at 6:06AM AKDT by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
Gale force southeast winds increase along the YK Delta into Norton Sound Wednesday afternoon and then turn southwesterly at gale force late Wednesday evening to Thursday morning as a Bering low moves from Saint Lawrence Island to Kivalina. This will bring elevated water levels of 2 to 5 feet above the normal high tideline, with the highest water levels projected to be over E Norton Sound, and lower levels for Nome and along the YK Delta.
Impacts include: The potential for water to move on top of the ice near the coast in some areas. Trails that cross ice near the coast may become inundated. Ice could push onto the beach, especially along south and west facing coast lines.
Residents near the coast should be vigilant of these potential impacts and stay tuned to the latest forecast updates at www.weather.gov/afg

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued April 9 at 2:58AM AKDT by NWS Anchorage AK
entry.summary:
Bands of moderate to heavy snow showers will move across Eastern Kenai Peninsula and Eastern Turnagain Arm through Tuesday evening. The first of these bands will move through the area early to mid Tuesday morning with the second late Tuesday morning through mid Tuesday afternoon. Snowfall rates may approach 1 to 2 inches per hour in heavier snow showers, reducing visibility to as low as one quarter mile at times. Motorists are urged to slow down and use caution when driving through heavy snow showers.
The highest snowfall accumulations are expected along Portage Glacier Road, where 5 to 10 inches of snow could fall. Elsewhere along the Seward Highway, 2 to 6 inches of snow, with locally higher amounts, are possible. Any snow accumulations on area roads this morning may turn slushy or wet by afternoon as temperatures warm into the mid 30s.
